# Shared Package Rules

## 1. Purpose and Responsibility

`packages/shared` is the single source of truth for:
- **All Zod validation schemas** for domain and API shapes (HTTP or not) — backend, frontend, and any `safeParse` / OpenAPI usage import from here
- **All TypeScript types** that describe payloads, DTOs, params, enums, and API data — in `packages/shared/src/types/` (prefer `z.infer` when a Zod schema exists)
- Environment schema — validates all env vars at startup
- Shared constants — values used across apps (e.g. Swagger tag order), via `@task-forge/shared/constant`

### 1.1 The golden rule (types and schemas live in shared)
**Declare every feature type and Zod schema in `packages/shared`** (`src/types/<feature>.types.ts` and `src/schemas/<feature>.schema.ts`). Do **not** add `*.types.ts` or `*.schema.ts` under `apps/backend/src/modules/` for DTOs, request bodies, service params, or integration payloads — import from `@task-forge/shared/types` and `@task-forge/shared/schemas` instead.

  ✓ belongs in `packages/shared`
    Any DTO / param / response / enum used by backend services or routes
    Zod schemas for validation, OpenAPI, or shared forms
    Types inferred from those schemas
    env, constants

  ✗ stays outside shared (not “shared types/schemas”)
    TypeORM **entities** — `apps/backend/.../internal/*.entity.ts` only
    Fastify **`FastifyRequest` / route handler generics** — backend only
    React **component props** and hooks — frontend only
    **`AppError` subclasses** — `apps/backend/.../<feature>.error.ts` only (classes, not data shapes)

---

## 2. File Structure

### 2.1 Folder structure
```
packages/shared/
├── src/
│   ├── env.schema.ts         Zod env validation — stays at root, never moves
│   ├── constant/
│   │   ├── index.ts          barrel — re-exports constants only
│   │   └── *.constants.ts    named constant modules (e.g. swagger.constants.ts)
│   ├── schemas/
│   │   ├── index.ts          barrel — exports all schemas
│   │   ├── common-schemas.ts error response schemas, pagination schema
│   │   ├── auth.schema.ts
│   │   ├── task.schema.ts
│   │   └── <feature>.schema.ts
│   └── types/
│       ├── index.ts          barrel — exports all types
│       ├── common-types.ts   ApiResponse, PaginationMeta, RouterConfig, LogType etc
│       ├── auth.types.ts
│       ├── task.types.ts
│       └── <feature>.types.ts
```

Note: There is no src/index.ts — import via sub-paths only.

### 2.2 File naming
All files use kebab-case:
  common-schemas.ts   ✓
  common-types.ts     ✓
  common.types.ts     ✗ — dot separator not allowed
  commonTypes.ts      ✗ — camelCase not allowed

### 2.3 Adding a new feature to shared
Backend work on a feature should start from shared types/schemas when introducing or changing payloads — do not add `*.types.ts` / `*.schema.ts` under `apps/backend/src/modules/<feature>/`.

```
1. Create src/schemas/<feature>.schema.ts (when Zod is needed)
2. Create or extend src/types/<feature>.types.ts (infer from Zod and/or plain types)
3. Export from src/schemas/index.ts
4. Export from src/types/index.ts
5. Rebuild: cd packages/shared && pnpm tsc
```

### 2.4 index.ts files are barrel exports only — no logic
`src/schemas/index.ts`, `src/types/index.ts`, and `src/constant/index.ts` must only contain
export statements. Never add logic, functions, or class definitions here.
There is no `src/index.ts`.

### 2.5 Comments
- **Do not** add unnecessary comments in schemas or types files (no restating field names or Zod chains).
- **Do** comment **only** when a rule encodes **non-obvious business or cross-app contract** (e.g. why a constraint exists for both FE and BE) and that context cannot live in the schema message alone.

---

## 3. Import Sub-paths

Four import paths are available — no main path:

  @task-forge/shared/schemas   — schemas only
  @task-forge/shared/types     — types only
  @task-forge/shared/env       — env object only (backend only)
  @task-forge/shared/constant  — shared constants (barrel)

### 3.1 Always use specific sub-paths — no main path import

  import { createTaskSchema } from '@task-forge/shared/schemas'    ✓
  import type { Task } from '@task-forge/shared/types'             ✓
  import { SWAGGER_TAG_DISPLAY_ORDER } from '@task-forge/shared/constant'   ✓
  import { createTaskSchema } from '@task-forge/shared'            ✗ — no main path
  import { createTaskSchema } from '../../packages/shared/src/...' ✗ — never direct

### 3.2 env sub-path is backend only
  import { env } from '@task-forge/shared/env'   ✓ backend only
  import { env } from '@task-forge/shared/env'   ✗ never in frontend

### 3.3 Never import env from main path or schemas path
  import { env } from '@task-forge/shared'          ✗
  import { env } from '@task-forge/shared/schemas'  ✗

---

## 4. Schema Rules (src/schemas/)

### 4.1 Always use Zod for schemas — never TypeBox or Joi
`src/schemas/` holds **Zod** definitions only. When runtime validation, OpenAPI, Fastify wiring, or `safeParse` is **not** needed for a shape, define a plain **`type` / `interface` in `src/types/`** only — never put that shape in `apps/backend` module files (see §5.1 and backend §6.1).

### 4.2 Schema file structure — schemas only in schemas/
src/schemas/ contains ONLY Zod schema definitions.
No types, no classes, no functions beyond schema definitions.

### 4.3 Schema naming convention
camelCase + Schema suffix:
  createTaskSchema   ✓
  updateTaskSchema   ✓
  taskParamsSchema   ✓
  CreateTaskSchema   ✗ — PascalCase wrong
  createTask         ✗ — missing Schema suffix

### 4.4 common-schemas.ts contains shared error and response schemas
These schemas are reused across ALL modules — never redefine per module:
  errorResponseSchema
  validationErrorResponseSchema
  unauthorizedResponseSchema
  forbiddenResponseSchema
  notFoundResponseSchema
  paginationMetaSchema
  successResponseSchema (factory that wraps a data schema into `{ success: true, data }`)

### 4.5 Base schema and derived request/DTO schemas
- Define one **base** Zod object per API entity (e.g. `userSchema`, `accountSchema`) with all field rules.
- Derive create/update/PATCH bodies with **`.pick()`**, **`.omit()`**, **`.extend()`**, and **`.partial()`** so validators are not duplicated in a new `z.object({ ... })`.
- Typical patterns: create = `.pick({ ... }).partial({ optionalFields })`; PATCH = `.omit({ id, ... }).partial()` (or `.pick().partial()` when only a subset is patchable).
- Keep derived schemas **next to** the base in the same file; name them `createXBodySchema`, `patchXBodySchema`, etc.
- If a request field is **not** on the entity (e.g. a one-off flag), add it with **`.extend({ flag: z.boolean().optional() })`** on a picked/omitted base — still avoid re-stating base field validators.
- When the wire shape cannot be expressed as pick/omit/partial of the base (e.g. required payload where the entity column is nullable), reuse pieces via a **shared inner schema** or **`base.shape.field`** instead of redefining the same constraints.

### 4.6 Always add meaningful validation messages
  z.string().min(2, 'Name must be at least 2 characters')   ✓
  z.string().min(2)                                          ✗

### 4.7 Route schemas per feature

- Each `<feature>.schema.ts` file MAY also export route-level schemas for Swagger,
  but only as plain objects that reference existing Zod schemas.
- Name route schemas with HTTP method + name, e.g.:

```ts
import { RouteTags } from '../types/openapi-route.types'

export const getHealthRouteSchema = {
  tags: [RouteTags.HEALTH],
  summary: 'Health Check',
  description: 'Returns server health status including database connection state',
  response: {
    200: successResponseSchema(healthDataSchema),
  },
}
```

- Use the **`RouteTags`** enum from `src/types/openapi-route.types.ts` for `tags` (never raw
  strings) so names stay aligned with OpenAPI. When adding a new area, extend **`RouteTags`**
  and append it to **`SWAGGER_TAG_DISPLAY_ORDER`** in `src/constant/swagger.constants.ts`.
- Always place these route schema exports at the **end of the file**, after all
  Zod schema definitions, to keep structure consistent across features.
- Optional **`requestBodyExample`**: inline a plain object (same shape as `body`) on the
  route schema object — do **not** extract a separate exported example constant. The
  backend Swagger plugin copies it to OpenAPI `example` for Swagger UI **Try it out**.
  See `OpenapiRouteSchemaExtension` in `src/types/openapi-route.types.ts`.

### 4.8 UUID validation for ID params
  id: z.string().uuid('Invalid ID format')   ✓
  id: z.string()                              ✗

---

## 5. Type Rules (src/types/)

### 5.1 Infer from Zod when a schema exists; otherwise plain types (always under `packages/shared`)
- **When a Zod schema exists** for the shape: **`export type X = z.infer<typeof xSchema>`** in `packages/shared/src/types/` ✓
- **When no schema is needed** (no validation / OpenAPI / `safeParse`): a plain **`interface` / `type`** in **`packages/shared/src/types/<feature>.types.ts`** ✓ — do not invent a Zod schema only to derive the type, and **do not** define the shape in `apps/backend/src/modules/`.

### 5.2 Type file structure — types only in types/
src/types/ contains ONLY TypeScript type definitions.
No Zod schemas, no classes, no functions.

### 5.3 Type naming convention
PascalCase, no I prefix, no Type suffix:
  CreateTaskInput   ✓
  TaskParams        ✓
  ICreateTask       ✗ — no I prefix
  CreateTaskType    ✗ — no Type suffix

### 5.4 common-types.ts contains shared utility types
  ApiResponse<T>
  PaginationMeta
  RouterConfig
  LogType
  ApiErrorResponse

### 5.5 Always use string for dates — never Date
TypeORM returns Date objects but JSON serialization converts them to strings.
  createdAt: string   ✓
  createdAt: Date     ✗

---

## 6. Environment Schema Rules

### 6.1 env.schema.ts stays at src/ root — never moves to schemas/
It has a dedicated sub-path export and is intentionally separated.

### 6.2 Adding a new environment variable
```
Step 1 — add to src/env.schema.ts
Step 2 — add to apps/backend/.env.development
Step 3 — add to apps/backend/.env.uat
Step 4 — add to apps/backend/.env.example (empty value + comment)
Step 5 — rebuild: cd packages/shared && pnpm tsc
Step 6 — use: import { env } from '@task-forge/shared/env'
```

---

## 7. Build Rules

### 7.1 Always rebuild after any change to packages/shared/src/
  cd packages/shared && pnpm tsc

### 7.2 Never commit dist/ folder
packages/shared/dist/ is git ignored. Always generated locally or in CI.

### 7.3 Verify dist structure after build
  packages/shared/dist/schemas/index.js ✓
  packages/shared/dist/types/index.js   ✓
  packages/shared/dist/env.schema.js    ✓
  packages/shared/dist/index.js         ✗ — must NOT exist
